onary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: occupational name for a merchant or trader, Middle English <i>chap(pe)man</i>, <i>chepman</i>, Old English <i>cēapmann</i>, <i>cēpemann</i>, a compound of <i>cēap</i> ‘barter, bargain, price, property’ + <i>mann</i> ‘man’.","Jewish: adopted probably for a like-sounding or like-meaning name in some other European language; see for example   Kaufman  .","History: This name was brought independently to North America from England by numerous different bearers from the 17th century onward. John Chapmen (sic) was one of the free planters who assented to the ‘Fundamental Agreement’ of the New Haven Colony on June 4, 1639."],"variants":[{"name":"Chatman","meanings":["English: altered form of   Chapman  ."]},{"name":"Kaufman","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Jewish Hyman, Meyer, Chaim, Emanuel, Moshe, Eytan, Herschel, Zvi, Ari, Aron.","Americanized form of German   Kaufmann  , and a variant of the same Jewish surname.","Jewish (Ashkenazic): from the personal name <i>Kaufman</i> meaning ‘merchant’. Compare   Koyfman   2."]},{"name":"Chipman","meanings":["English: from Middle English <i>chipman</i> (Old English <i>cȳp(e)mann</i>), a side form of <i>chapman</i>, <i>chepman</i> ‘merchant, trader’; see   Chapman  , with which this name was interchangeable."]},{"name":"Copeman","meanings":["English (Norfolk and Suffolk): patronymic from the early Middle English personal name <i>Cop(e)man</i>, an Anglicized form of Old Scandinavian <i>Kaupmaðr</i>. It is a transferred use of Old Scandinavian <i>kaupmaðr</i> (Old Danish <i>køpman</i>) ‘merchant’, cognate with Old English <i>cēapmann</i> (see   Chapman  ), but there is no evidence for the occupational term in Middle English.","Americanized form of North German   Koopmann   or Dutch   Koopman  ."]}]},{"name":"Margaret","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."],"variants":[{"name":"Margareta","meanings":["From the Latin form of Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>.  See  <b>Margaret</b>   ."]},{"name":"Margaretta","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705201,"age":49,"year":"1549","julianDay":2286821,"title":"Book of Common Prayer","description":"Book of Common Prayer, a product of the English Reformation, was published in 1549 for assistance in the administration of the sacraments and other rites and ceremonies of the church according to the use of the Church of England. The book outlined morning, evening, and communion prayers and orders for baptism and marriage, thus making England a truly Protestant state.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Book_of_Common_Prayer","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Book of Common Prayer","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"Margaret Chapman was born in 1500, in Hedgerley, Buckinghamshire, England. She married Robert Devon Treadway before 1523, in Hedgerley, Buckinghamshire, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 2 sons. She died in 1550, at the age of 50."},"et":{"1500–1550":"1500–1550","1500–1594":"1500–1594","1532–1558":"1532–1558","1534–Male":"1534–Surnud","before 1523":"enne 1523","1558":"1558","1534":"1534","1500":"1500","1532":"1532","1550":"1550","1594":"1594","1549":"1549","Hedgerley, Buckinghamshire, England":"Hedgerley, Buckinghamshire, England","Saint Mary the Virgin Church, Hedgerley, Buckinghamshire, England":"Hedgerley, Buckinghamshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1500–1550":"1500–1550","1500–1594":"1500–1594","1532–1558":"1532–1558","1534–Male":"1534–Kuollut","before 1523":"ennen vuotta 1523","1558":"1558","1534":"1534","1500":"1500","1532":"1532","1550":"1550","1594":"1594","1549":"1549","Hedgerley, Buckinghamshire, England":"Hedgerley, Buckinghamshire, England","Saint Mary the Virgin Church, Hedgerley, Buckinghamshire, England":"Hedgerley, Buckinghamshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"1500–1550":"1500–1550","1500–1594":"1500–1594"